# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: standard-ml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In computer science, **functional programming** is a programming paradigm where programs are constructed by applying and composing functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It is a declarative programming paradigm in which function definitions are trees of expressions that map values to other values, rather than a sequence of imperative statements which update the running state of the program.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In functional programming, functions are treated as first-class entities, meaning that they can be bound to names (including local identifiers), passed as arguments, and returned from other functions, just as any other data type can.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This allows programs to be written in a declarative and composable style, where small functions are combined in a modular manner.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming is sometimes treated as synonymous with purely functional programming, a subset of functional programming that treats all functions as deterministic mathematical functions, or pure functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] When a pure function is called with some given arguments, it will always return the same result, and cannot be affected by any mutable state or other side effects.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This is in contrast with impure procedures, common in imperative programming, which can have side effects (such as modifying the program's state or taking input from a user).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Proponents of purely functional programming claim that by restricting side effects, programs can have fewer bugs, be easier to debug and test, and be more suited to formal verification.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming has its roots in academia, evolving from the lambda calculus, a formal system of computation based only on functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming has historically been less popular than imperative programming, but many functional languages are seeing use today in industry and education, including Common Lisp, Scheme, Clojure, Wolfram Language, Racket, Erlang, Elixir, OCaml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lean is a functional programming language commonly used for verifying mathematical theorems.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming is also key to some languages that have found success in specific domains, like JavaScript in the Web, R in statistics, J, K and Q in financial analysis, and XQuery/XSLT for XML.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Domain-specific declarative languages like SQL and Lex/Yacc use some elements of functional programming, such as not allowing mutable values.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In addition, many other programming languages support programming in a functional style or have implemented features from functional programming, such as C++ (since C++11), C#, Kotlin, Perl, PHP, Python, Go, Rust, Raku, Scala, and Java (since Java 8).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The lambda calculus, developed in the 1930s by Alonzo Church, is a formal system of computation built from function application.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In 1937 Alan Turing proved that the lambda calculus and Turing machines are equivalent models of computation, showing that the lambda calculus is Turing complete.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lambda calculus forms the basis of all functional programming languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] An equivalent theoretical formulation, combinatory logic, was developed by Moses Schönfinkel and Haskell Curry in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Church later developed a weaker system, the simply typed lambda calculus, which extended the lambda calculus by assigning a data type to all terms.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This forms the basis for statically typed functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The first high-level functional programming language, Lisp, was developed in the late 1950s for the IBM 700/7000 series of scientific computers by John McCarthy while at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lisp functions were defined using Church's lambda notation, extended with a label construct to allow recursive functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lisp first introduced many paradigmatic features of functional programming, though early Lisps were multi-paradigm languages, and incorporated support for numerous programming styles as new paradigms evolved.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Later dialects, such as Scheme and Clojure, and offshoots such as Dylan and Julia, sought to simplify and rationalise Lisp around a cleanly functional core, while Common Lisp was designed to preserve and update the paradigmatic features of the numerous older dialects it replaced.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Information Processing Language (IPL), 1956, is sometimes cited as the first computer-based functional programming language.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It is an assembly-style language for manipulating lists of symbols.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It does have a notion of *generator*, which amounts to a function that accepts a function as an argument, and, since it is a low-level programming language, code can be data, so IPL can be regarded as having higher-order functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, it relies heavily on the mutating list structure and similar imperative features.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Iverson developed APL in the early 1960s, described in his 1962 book *A Programming Language* (ISBN 9780471430148).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] APL was the primary influence on John Backus's FP.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In the early 1990s, Iverson and Roger Hui created J.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In the mid-1990s, Arthur Whitney, who had previously worked with Iverson, created K, which is used commercially in financial industries along with its descendant Q.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In the mid-1960s, Peter Landin invented SECD machine, the first abstract machine for a functional programming language, described a correspondence between ALGOL 60 and the lambda calculus, and proposed the ISWIM programming language.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] John Backus presented FP in his 1977 Turing Award lecture "Can Programming Be Liberated From the von Neumann Style?
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] A Functional Style and its Algebra of Programs".
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] He defines functional programs as being built up in a hierarchical way by means of "combining forms" that allow an "algebra of programs"; in modern language, this means that functional programs follow the principle of compositionality.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Backus's paper popularized research into functional programming, though it emphasized function-level programming rather than the lambda-calculus style now associated with functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The 1973 language ML was created by Robin Milner at the University of Edinburgh, and David Turner developed the language SASL at the University of St Andrews.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Also in Edinburgh in the 1970s, Burstall and Darlington developed the functional language NPL.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] NPL was based on Kleene Recursion Equations and was first introduced in their work on program transformation.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Burstall, MacQueen and Sannella then incorporated the polymorphic type checking from ML to produce the language Hope.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] ML eventually developed into several dialects, the most common of which are now OCaml and Standard ML.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Steele and Gerald Jay Sussman developed Scheme, as described in the Lambda Papers and the 1985 textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs*.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Scheme was the first dialect of lisp to use lexical scoping and to require tail-call optimization, features that encourage functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In the 1980s, Per Martin-Löf developed intuitionistic type theory (also called *constructive* type theory), which associated functional programs with constructive proofs expressed as dependent types.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This led to new approaches to interactive theorem proving and has influenced the development of subsequent functional programming languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The lazy functional language, Miranda, developed by David Turner, initially appeared in 1985 and had a strong influence on Haskell.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] With Miranda being proprietary, Haskell began with a consensus in 1987 to form an open standard for functional programming research; implementation releases have been ongoing as of 1990.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] More recently it has found use in niches such as parametric CAD in the OpenSCAD language built on the CGAL framework, although its restriction on reassigning values (all values are treated as constants) has led to confusion among users who are unfamiliar with functional programming as a concept.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming continues to be used in commercial settings.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] A number of concepts and paradigms are specific to functional programming, and generally foreign to imperative programming (including object-oriented programming).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, programming languages often cater to several programming paradigms, so programmers using "mostly imperative" languages may have utilized some of these concepts.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are functions that can either take other functions as arguments or return them as results.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In calculus, an example of a higher-order function is the differential operator $d/dx$ , which returns the derivative of a function f .
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are closely related to first-class functions in that higher-order functions and first-class functions both allow functions as arguments and results of other functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Higher-order functions enable partial application or currying, a technique that applies a function to its arguments one at a time, with each application returning a new function that accepts the next argument.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This lets a programmer succinctly express, for example, the successor function as the addition operator partially applied to the natural number one.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Pure functions (or expressions) have no side effects (memory or I/O).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some compilers, such as gcc, add extra keywords for a programmer to explicitly mark external functions as pure, to enable such optimizations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Fortran 95 also lets functions be designated *pure*.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] C++11 added `constexpr` keyword with similar semantics.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Iteration (looping) in functional languages is usually accomplished via recursion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Recursive functions invoke themselves, letting an operation be repeated until it reaches the base case.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In general, recursion requires maintaining a stack, which consumes space in a linear amount to the depth of recursion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This could make recursion prohibitively expensive to use instead of imperative loops.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, a special form of recursion known as tail recursion can be recognized and optimized by a compiler into the same code used to implement iteration in imperative languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Tail recursion optimization can be implemented by transforming the program into continuation passing style during compiling, among other approaches.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The Scheme language standard requires implementations to support proper tail recursion, meaning they must allow an unbounded number of active tail calls.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Proper tail recursion is not simply an optimization; it is a language feature that assures users that they can use recursion to express a loop and doing so would be safe-for-space.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Moreover, contrary to its name, it accounts for all tail calls, not just tail recursion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] While proper tail recursion is usually implemented by turning code into imperative loops, implementations might implement it in other ways.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For example, Chicken intentionally maintains a stack and lets the stack overflow.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, when this happens, its garbage collector will claim space back, allowing an unbounded number of active tail calls even though it does not turn tail recursion into a loop.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Common patterns of recursion can be abstracted away using higher-order functions, with catamorphisms and anamorphisms (or "folds" and "unfolds") being the most obvious examples.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Such recursion schemes play a role analogous to built-in control structures such as loops in imperative languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some special purpose languages such as Rocq allow only well-founded recursion and are strongly normalizing (nonterminating computations can be expressed only with infinite streams of values called codata).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] As a consequence, these languages fail to be Turing complete and expressing certain functions in them is impossible, but they can still express a wide class of interesting computations while avoiding the problems introduced by unrestricted recursion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming limited to well-founded recursion with a few other constraints is called total functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional languages can be categorized by whether they use *strict (eager)* or *non-strict (lazy)* evaluation, concepts that refer to how function arguments are processed when an expression is being evaluated.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The technical difference is in the denotational semantics of expressions containing failing or divergent computations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Under strict evaluation, the evaluation of any term containing a failing subterm fails.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] fails under strict evaluation because of the division by zero in the third element of the list.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Under lazy evaluation, the length function returns the value 4 (i.e., the number of items in the list), since evaluating it does not attempt to evaluate the terms making up the list.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In brief, strict evaluation always fully evaluates function arguments before invoking the function.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation does not evaluate function arguments unless their values are required to evaluate the function call itself.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The usual implementation strategy for lazy evaluation in functional languages is graph reduction.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation is used by default in several pure functional languages, including Miranda, Clean, and Haskell.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Hughes 1984 argues for lazy evaluation as a mechanism for improving program modularity through separation of concerns, by easing independent implementation of producers and consumers of data streams.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 describes some difficulties that lazy evaluation introduces, particularly in analyzing a program's storage requirements, and proposes an operational semantics to aid in such analysis.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Harper 2009 proposes including both strict and lazy evaluation in the same language, using the language's type system to distinguish them.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some research-oriented functional languages such as Rocq, Agda, Cayenne, and Epigram are based on intuitionistic type theory, which lets types depend on terms.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] These type systems do not have decidable type inference and are difficult to understand and program with.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] But dependent types can express arbitrary propositions in higher-order logic.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Through the Curry–Howard isomorphism, then, well-typed programs in these languages become a means of writing formal mathematical proofs from which a compiler can generate certified code.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] While these languages are mainly of interest in academic research (including in formalized mathematics), they have begun to be used in engineering as well.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Compcert is a compiler for a subset of the language C that is written in Rocq and formally verified.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] A limited form of dependent types called generalized algebraic data types (GADT's) can be implemented in a way that provides some of the benefits of dependently typed programming while avoiding most of its inconvenience.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] GADT's are available in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, in OCaml and in Scala, and have been proposed as additions to other languages including Java and C#.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programs do not have assignment statements, that is, the value of a variable in a functional program never changes once defined.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This eliminates any chances of side effects because any variable can be replaced with its actual value at any point of execution.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] So, functional programs are referentially transparent.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Consider C assignment statement `x = x * 10`, this changes the value assigned to the variable `x`.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Let us say that the initial value of `x` was `1`, then two consecutive evaluations of the variable `x` yields `10` and `100` respectively.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Clearly, replacing `x = x * 10` with either `10` or `100` gives a program a different meaning, and so the expression *is not* referentially transparent.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In fact, assignment statements are never referentially transparent.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Now, consider another function such as `int plusOne(int x) { return x + 1; }` *is* transparent, as it does not implicitly change the input x and thus has no such side effects.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programs exclusively use this type of function and are therefore referentially transparent.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way to their imperative counterparts.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For example, the array with constant access and update times is a basic component of most imperative languages, and many imperative data-structures, such as the hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by maps or random access lists, which admit purely functional implementation, but have logarithmic access and update times.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures have persistence, a property of keeping previous versions of the data structure unmodified.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In Clojure, persistent data structures are used as functional alternatives to their imperative counterparts.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Persistent vectors, for example, use trees for partial updating.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Calling the insert method will result in some but not all nodes being created.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming is very different from imperative programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The most significant differences stem from the fact that functional programming avoids side effects, which are used in imperative programming to implement state and I/O.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Pure functional programming completely prevents side-effects and provides referential transparency.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are rarely used in older imperative programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] A traditional imperative program might use a loop to traverse and modify a list.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] A functional program, on the other hand, would probably use a higher-order "map" function that takes a function and a list, generating and returning a new list by applying the function to each list item.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The following two examples (written in Java) achieve the same effect: they multiply all even numbers in an array by 10 and add them all, storing the final sum in the variable `result`.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Sometimes the abstractions offered by functional programming might lead to development of more robust code that avoids certain issues that might arise when building upon large amount of complex, imperative code, such as off-by-one errors (see Greenspun's tenth rule).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] There are tasks (for example, maintaining a bank account balance) that often seem most naturally implemented with state.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Pure functional programming performs these tasks, and I/O tasks such as accepting user input and printing to the screen, in a different way.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The pure functional programming language Haskell implements them using monads, derived from category theory.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Monads offer a way to abstract certain types of computational patterns, including (but not limited to) modeling of computations with mutable state (and other side effects such as I/O) in an imperative manner without losing purity.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] While existing monads may be easy to apply in a program, given appropriate templates and examples, many students find them difficult to understand conceptually, e.g., when asked to define new monads (which is sometimes needed for certain types of libraries).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional languages also simulate states by passing around immutable states.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This can be done by making a function accept the state as one of its parameters, and return a new state together with the result, leaving the old state unchanged.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Impure functional languages usually include a more direct method of managing mutable state.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Clojure, for example, uses managed references that can be updated by applying pure functions to the current state.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This kind of approach enables mutability while still promoting the use of pure functions as the preferred way to express computations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Alternative methods such as Hoare logic and uniqueness have been developed to track side effects in programs.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some modern research languages use effect systems to make the presence of side effects explicit.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming languages are typically less efficient in their use of CPU and memory than imperative languages such as C and Pascal.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This is related to the fact that some mutable data structures like arrays have a very straightforward implementation using present hardware.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Flat arrays may be accessed very efficiently with deeply pipelined CPUs, prefetched efficiently through caches (with no complex pointer chasing), or handled with SIMD instructions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It is also not easy to create their equally efficient general-purpose immutable counterparts.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For purely functional languages, the worst-case slowdown is logarithmic in the number of memory cells used, because mutable memory can be represented by a purely functional data structure with logarithmic access time (such as a balanced tree).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, such slowdowns are not universal.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For programs that perform intensive numerical computations, functional languages such as OCaml and Clean are only slightly slower than C according to The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For programs that handle large matrices and multidimensional databases, array functional languages (such as J and K) were designed with speed optimizations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Immutability of data can in many cases lead to execution efficiency by allowing the compiler to make assumptions that are unsafe in an imperative language, thus increasing opportunities for inline expansion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Even if the involved copying that may seem implicit when dealing with persistent immutable data structures might seem computationally costly, some functional programming languages, like Clojure solve this issue by implementing mechanisms for safe memory sharing between *formally* *immutable* data.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This is how for example `java.util.concurrent` classes are implemented, where some of them are immutable variants of the corresponding classes that are not suitable for concurrent use.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming languages often have a concurrency model that instead of shared state and synchronization, leverages message passing mechanisms (such as the actor model, where each actor is a container for state, behavior, child actors and a message queue).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This approach is common in Erlang/Elixir or Akka.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation may also speed up the program, even asymptotically, whereas it may slow it down at most by a constant factor (however, it may introduce memory leaks if used improperly).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 discusses theoretical issues related to memory leaks from lazy evaluation, and O'Sullivan *et al.* 2008 give some practical advice for analyzing and fixing them.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, the most general implementations of lazy evaluation making extensive use of dereferenced code and data perform poorly on modern processors with deep pipelines and multi-level caches (where a cache miss may cost hundreds of cycles).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some functional programming languages might not optimize abstractions such as higher order functions like "map" or "filter" as efficiently as the underlying imperative operations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] has the mean execution time of 4.76 ms, while the second one, in which `.equals` is a direct invocation of the underlying Java method, has a mean execution time of 2.8 μs – roughly 1700 times faster.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Part of that can be attributed to the type checking and exception handling involved in the implementation of `even?`.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For instance the lo library for Go, which implements various higher-order functions common in functional programming languages using generics.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In a benchmark provided by the library's author, calling `map` is 4% slower than an equivalent `for` loop and has the same allocation profile, which can be attributed to various compiler optimizations, such as inlining.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] One distinguishing feature of Rust are *zero-cost abstractions*.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This means that using them imposes no additional runtime overhead.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] This is achieved thanks to the compiler using loop unrolling, where each iteration of a loop, be it imperative or using iterators, is converted into a standalone Assembly instruction, without the overhead of the loop controlling code.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] If an iterative operation writes to an array, the resulting array's elements will be stored in specific CPU registers, allowing for constant-time access at runtime.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It is possible to use a functional style of programming in languages that are not traditionally considered functional languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For example, both D and Fortran 95 explicitly support pure functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] JavaScript, Lua, Python and Go had first class functions from their inception.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Python had support for "lambda", "map", "reduce", and "filter" in 1994, as well as closures in Python 2.2, though Python 3 relegated "reduce" to the `functools` standard library module.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] First-class functions have been introduced into other mainstream languages such as Perl 5.0 in 1994, PHP 5.3, Visual Basic 9, C# 3.0, C++11, and Kotlin.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In Perl, lambda, map, reduce, filter, and closures are fully supported and frequently used.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The book Higher-Order Perl, released in 2005, was written to provide an expansive guide on using Perl for functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In PHP, anonymous classes, closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In Java, anonymous classes can sometimes be used to simulate closures; however, anonymous classes are not always proper replacements to closures because they have more limited capabilities.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Java 8 supports lambda expressions as a replacement for some anonymous classes.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In C#, anonymous classes are not necessary, because closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style in C#.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Many object-oriented design patterns are expressible in functional programming terms: for example, the strategy pattern simply dictates use of a higher-order function, and the visitor pattern roughly corresponds to a catamorphism, or fold.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Similarly, the idea of immutable data from functional programming is often included in imperative programming languages, for example the tuple in Python, which is an immutable array, and Object.freeze() in JavaScript.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Logic programming can be viewed as a generalisation of functional programming, in which functions are a special case of relations.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] For example, the function, mother(X) = Y, (every X has only one mother Y) can be represented by the relation mother(X, Y).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Whereas functions have a strict input-output pattern of arguments, relations can be queried with any pattern of inputs and outputs.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Compared with relational syntax, functional syntax is a more compact notation for nested functions.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, the difference between the two representations is simply syntactic.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Ciao transforms the function-like notation into relational form and executes the resulting logic program using the standard Prolog execution strategy.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Emacs, a highly extensible text editor family uses its own Lisp dialect for writing plugins.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] The original author of the most popular Emacs implementation, GNU Emacs and Emacs Lisp, Richard Stallman considers Lisp one of his favorite programming languages.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Spreadsheets can be considered a form of pure, zeroth-order, strict-evaluation functional programming system.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] However, spreadsheets generally lack higher-order functions as well as code reuse, and in some implementations, also lack recursion.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Several extensions have been developed for spreadsheet programs to enable higher-order and reusable functions, but so far remain primarily academic in nature.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Due to their composability, functional programming paradigms can be suitable for microservices-based architectures.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming is an active area of research in the field of programming language theory.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] There are several peer-reviewed publication venues focusing on functional programming, including the International Conference on Functional Programming, the Journal of Functional Programming, and the Symposium on Trends in Functional Programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming has been employed in a wide range of industrial applications.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Scheme, a dialect of Lisp, was used as the basis for several applications on early Apple Macintosh computers and has been applied to problems such as training-simulation software and telescope control.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] OCaml, which was introduced in the mid-1990s, has seen commercial use in areas such as financial analysis, driver verification, industrial robot programming and static analysis of embedded software.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Haskell, though initially intended as a research language, has also been applied in areas such as aerospace systems, hardware design and web programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Other functional programming languages that have seen use in industry include Scala, F#, Wolfram Language, Lisp, Standard ML and Clojure.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Scala has been widely used in Data science, while ClojureScript, Elm or PureScript are some of the functional frontend programming languages used in production.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional "platforms" have been popular in finance for risk analytics (particularly with large investment banks).
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Risk factors are coded as functions that form interdependent graphs (categories) to measure correlations in market shifts, similar in manner to Gröbner basis optimizations but also for regulatory frameworks such as Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Given the use of OCaml and Caml variations in finance, these systems are sometimes considered related to a categorical abstract machine.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Functional programming is heavily influenced by category theory.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Many universities teach functional programming.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Some treat it as an introductory programming concept while others first teach imperative programming methods.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] Outside of computer science, functional programming is used to teach problem-solving, algebraic and geometric concepts.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] It has also been used to teach classical mechanics, as in the book *Structure and Interpretation of Classical Mechanics*.
[src:standard-ml/functional-programming] In particular, Scheme has been a relatively popular choice for teaching programming for years.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] ML started development by Robin Milner upon his arrival at University of Edinburgh in 1973 with the help of research assistants Lockwood Morris and Malcolm Newey, both postdocs from Stanford who were hired by Milner.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Michael Gordon, Christopher Wadsworth, and other graduate students joined in research by 1975.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Historically, ML was conceived to develop proof tactics in the LCF theorem prover and succeed the previous iteration *Stanford LCF*, trying to solve issues regarding space utilization and proof extensibility.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] ML acted as both a metalanguage (hence the name) and command (REPL) language for the LCF system*.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] PPLAMBDA*, a language that was conceptually a combination of the first-order predicate calculus and the simply typed polymorphic lambda calculus, was the underlying language that theorem statements were more directly constructed in.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] As ML was being developed, Milner wrote the paper *A theory of type polymorphism in programming* in 1978, which laid out the ideas of what it meant for a program to be well-typed in the context of a polymorphic (generic) type system.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] He used ML as the case-study application of the theorems developed and noted the theoretical challenges that arose with development that had yet to have been solved.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The design of the first version of ML was finalized, and subsequently documented in the 1979 book *Edinburgh LCF* by Milner along with Gordon and Wadsworth.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] After *Edinburgh LCF* was established with the publication of the same name, interest in the language grew and several implementations, all with slight alterations in design and features, were underway by several parties.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Luca Cardelli created *Cardelli ML*, or *VAX ML*, which eventually grew into a standalone dialect fit for general-purpose computing, specified with the paper *ML under Unix*.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Gérard Huet at Inria began porting the source code from Stanford Lisp to various other dialects of Lisp in "Project Formel".
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The port to Franz Lisp was further developed by Larry Paulson, whose version eventually was coined *Cambridge LCF*.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] This version of the LCF was subsequently updated to use an early version of Standard ML, and has been uploaded to GitHub.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Concerns with the splintering of both design and implementation leading to duplicated work was raised in this meeting.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Although Milner seemed open to the spirit of experimentation in the meeting, further discussions and meetings were had between Bernard Sufrin and Milner, where Sufrin urged Milner to unify the design of ML.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] These correspondences were later referenced in the second draft of Milner's proposal for Standard ML.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The most notable inspiration of the syntax of ML can be traced to ISWIM, a language that was described as "lambda calculus with syntactic sugar".
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] ML was designed with a strong static type system that allowed the user to define abstract types with parametric polymorphism and was checked at compile-time.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] It also had automatic type inference, which afforded ML the ease-of-use of dynamic languages of the time such as Lisp or POP-2 by foregoing the need for explicit type annotations.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The following examples are very closely derived from *Edinburgh LCF*, showing a rough overview of the syntax and features of ML.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The `#` character at the start of a line denotes user input, and lines without it are system responses showing the value and its inferred type.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Note that this section is not meant to act as a comprehensive set of language features that ML contains, rather a subset to give a sense for the language.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Refer to *Edinburgh LCF* for a more rigorous definition.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Expressions are evaluated by typing them followed by `;;` and a return character.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The identifier `it` holds the result of the last-evaluated expression.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Function application is higher precedent than mathematical operators, so `f 3 + 4` means `(f 3) + 4`.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Functions defined with multiple parameters are curried, so passing one parameter into the function will return a function that will accept the second, and so on.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Recursive functions require `letrec` so the function name is in scope within its body.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] `hd` and `tl` are built-in functions that return the head and tail; `.` is cons (prepend); `@` is append.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Mutable variables are declared with `letref` and updated with `:=`.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Tokens are ML's string type, delimited by `; double backticks create token lists.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Abstract types are declared with `abstype`, which creates a new type and defines the functions that work with it, while keeping the internal structure (the concrete type it's built from) hidden.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Abstract recursive types are declared with `absrectype`, which allows the type to be used in its own definition.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] There is a similar keyword `lettype`, which is used for more basic type aliasing.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Inside the operation definitions (the `with` block), the type's name can be prepended with `abs` to box values in the type and `rep` to unbox values.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] The characters `+` and `#` in type definitions signify sum types (tagged unions) and product types (tuples), respectively, with `#` having a higher precedence.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] ML on LCF provided several helper functions used in the example above.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Operating on sum types `+`, the functions `inl` and `inr` inject values into the left or right side of a sum type.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] `outl` extracts from left injections (fails if given a right injection), and `outr` extracts from right injections (fails if given a left injection).
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] For product types `#`, the extraction functions are `fst` and `snd`, which extract the first and second components of a pair.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] Product types are constructed using the comma infix operator.
[src:standard-ml/ml-programming-language] In the tree example above, `comptree` takes a single parameter that is a pair pattern `(y, t1, t2)`, which destructures the pair into its three components.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Standard ML is a modern dialect of ML, the language used in the Logic for Computable Functions (LCF) theorem-proving project.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] It is distinctive among widely used languages in that it has a formal specification, given as typing rules and operational semantics in *The Definition of Standard ML*, originally released in 1990, with a second and final revision being released in 1997.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Standard ML is a functional programming language with some impure features.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Programs written in Standard ML consist of expressions in contrast to statements or commands, although some expressions of type unit are only evaluated for their side-effects.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Like all functional languages, a key feature of Standard ML is the function, which is used for abstraction.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] An SML compiler must infer the static type `val factorial : int -> int` without user-supplied type annotations.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] It has to deduce that `n` is only used with integer expressions, and must therefore itself be an integer, and that all terminal expressions are integer expressions.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Here, the keyword `val` introduces a binding of an identifier to a value, `fn` introduces an anonymous function, and `rec` allows the definition to be self-referential.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The encapsulation of an invariant-preserving tail-recursive tight loop with one or more accumulator parameters within an invariant-free outer function, as seen here, is a common idiom in Standard ML.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A type synonym is defined with the keyword `type`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Here is a type synonym for points on a plane, and functions computing the distances between two points, and the area of a triangle with the given corners as per Heron's formula.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] (These definitions will be used in subsequent examples).
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Standard ML provides strong support for algebraic datatypes (ADT).
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A data type can be thought of as a disjoint union of tuples (or a "sum of products").
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] They are easy to define and easy to use, largely because of pattern matching, and most Standard ML implementations' pattern-exhaustiveness checking and pattern redundancy checking.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] In object-oriented programming languages, a disjoint union can be expressed as class hierarchies.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] However, in contrast to class hierarchies, ADTs are closed.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Thus, the extensibility of ADTs is orthogonal to the extensibility of class hierarchies.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Class hierarchies can be extended with new subclasses which implement the same interface, while the functions of ADTs can be extended for the fixed set of constructors.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Note that a type synonym cannot be recursive; datatypes are necessary to define recursive constructors.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Patterns are matched in the order in which they are defined.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] C programmers can use tagged unions, dispatching on tag values, to do what ML does with datatypes and pattern matching.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Nevertheless, while a C program decorated with appropriate checks will, in a sense, be as robust as the corresponding ML program, those checks will of necessity be dynamic; ML's static checks provide strong guarantees about the correctness of the program at compile time.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Pattern-exhaustiveness checking will make sure that each constructor of the datatype is matched by at least one pattern.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] There is no pattern for the `Triangle` case in the `center` function.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The compiler will issue a warning that the case expression is not exhaustive, and if a `Triangle` is passed to this function at runtime, `exception Match` will be raised.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Any value that would match the pattern in the second clause would also match the pattern in the first clause, so the second clause is unreachable.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Therefore, this definition as a whole exhibits redundancy, and causes a compile-time warning.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] If control gets past the first pattern (`Circle`), we know the shape must be either a `Square` or a `Triangle`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] In either of those cases, we know the shape has corners, so we can return `true` without discerning the actual shape.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Exceptions are raised with the keyword `raise` and handled with the pattern matching `handle` construct.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The exception system can implement non-local exit; this optimization technique is suitable for functions like the following.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] When `exception Zero` is raised, control leaves the function `List.foldl` altogether.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Consider the alternative: the value 0 would be returned, it would be multiplied by the next integer in the list, the resulting value (inevitably 0) would be returned, and so on.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The raising of the exception allows control to skip over the entire chain of frames and avoid the associated computation.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Note the use of the underscore (`_`) as a wildcard pattern.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The same optimization can be obtained with a tail call.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Standard ML's advanced module system allows programs to be decomposed into hierarchically organized *structures* of logically related type and value definitions.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Modules provide not only namespace control but also abstraction, in the sense that they allow the definition of abstract data types.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Three main syntactic constructs comprise the module system: signatures, structures and functors.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A *signature* is an interface, usually thought of as a type for a structure; it specifies the names of all entities provided by the structure, the arity of each type component, the type of each value component, and the signature of each substructure.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The definitions of type components are optional; type components whose definitions are hidden are *abstract types*.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This signature describes a module that provides a polymorphic type `'a queue`, `exception QueueError`, and values that define basic operations on queues.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A *structure* is a module; it consists of a collection of types, exceptions, values and structures (called *substructures*) packaged together into a logical unit.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This definition declares that `structure TwoListQueue` implements `signature QUEUE`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Furthermore, the *opaque ascription* denoted by `:>` states that any types which are not defined in the signature (i.e.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] `type 'a queue`) should be abstract, meaning that the definition of a queue as a pair of lists is not visible outside the module.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The structure implements all of the definitions in the signature.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A *functor* is a function from structures to structures; that is, a functor accepts one or more arguments, which are usually structures of a given signature, and produces a structure as its result.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Functors are used to implement generic data structures and algorithms.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] One popular algorithm for breadth-first search of trees makes use of queues.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Within `functor BFS`, the representation of the queue is not visible.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] More concretely, there is no way to select the first list in the two-list queue, if that is indeed the representation being used.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This data abstraction mechanism makes the breadth-first search truly agnostic to the queue's implementation.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This is in general desirable; in this case, the queue structure can safely maintain any logical invariants on which its correctness depends behind the bulletproof wall of abstraction.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Snippets of SML code are most easily studied by entering them into an interactive top-level.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Here, the classic mergesort algorithm is implemented in three functions: split, merge and mergesort.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Also note the absence of types, with the exception of the syntax `op ::` and `[]` which signify lists.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This code will sort lists of any type, so long as a consistent ordering function `cmp` is defined.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Using Hindley–Milner type inference, the types of all variables can be inferred, even complicated types such as that of the function `cmp`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Merge uses a local function loop for efficiency.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The inner `loop` is defined in terms of cases: when both lists are non-empty (`x :: xs`) and when one list is empty (`[]`).
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This function merges two sorted lists into one sorted list.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Note how the accumulator `acc` is built backwards, then reversed before being returned.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This is a common technique, since `'a list` is represented as a linked list; this technique requires more clock time, but the asymptotics are not worse.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] `fun part` is a closure that consumes an order operator `op <<`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The `IntInf` module provides arbitrary-precision integer arithmetic.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Moreover, integer literals may be used as arbitrary-precision integers without the programmer having to do anything.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Curried functions have many applications, such as eliminating redundant code.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] For example, a module may require functions of type `a -> b`, but it is more convenient to write functions of type `a * c -> b` where there is a fixed relationship between the objects of type `a` and `c`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A function of type `c -> (a * c -> b) -> a -> b` can factor out this commonality.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This is an example of the adapter pattern.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The type of `fun d` indicates that it maps a "float" onto a function with the type `(real -> real) -> real -> real`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] This allows us to partially apply arguments, known as currying.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] In this case, function `d` can be specialised by partially applying it with the argument `delta`.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] A good choice for `delta` when using this algorithm is the cube root of the machine epsilon.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The inferred type indicates that `d'` expects a function with the type `real -> real` as its first argument.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] We can compute an approximation to the derivative of $f(x)=x^{3}-x-1$ at $x=3$ .
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The Basis Library has been standardized and ships with most implementations.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] It provides modules for trees, arrays, and other data structures, and input/output and system interfaces.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] For numerical computing, a Matrix module exists (but is currently broken), https://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/project/pscico/pscico/src/matrix/README.html.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] For graphics, cairo-sml is an open source interface to the Cairo graphics library.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] For machine learning, a library for graphical models exists.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] All of these implementations are open-source and freely available.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] Most are implemented themselves in Standard ML.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] There are no longer any commercial implementations; Harlequin, now defunct, once produced a commercial IDE and compiler called MLWorks which passed on to Xanalys and was later open-sourced after it was acquired by Ravenbrook Limited on April 26, 2013.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The IT University of Copenhagen's entire enterprise architecture is implemented in around 100,000 lines of SML, including staff records, payroll, course administration and feedback, student project management, and web-based self-service interfaces.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] The proof assistants HOL4, Isabelle, LEGO, and Twelf are written in Standard ML.
[src:standard-ml/standard-ml] It is also used by compiler writers and integrated circuit designers such as ARM.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:standard-ml/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
